@node "Main" "LivingShuffle.guide/Main"
@{u}LivingShuffle v1.2@{uu}

LivingShuffle is another one of those fine modules for the famous
Garshneblanker screensaver.

This module implements the good old "shuffle" or "puzzle" blanker.
BUT this one can show a @{b}living@{ub} puzzle, which means the
contents of the puzzle pieces are continuously updated from the
source screen.
If you start this blanker you will at first probably notice nothing
special and then you'll see the pieces start shuffling around.
But if you first start a fractal calculator and then blank the
screen you'll know what @{b}living@{ub} means ;-}


A last hint for those preferences fiddler:
If you are running programs like mouse-pointer-following-eyes or
little clocks in some screen edges, try adjusting the row and column
values so that the little windows completely fit in one piece of the
puzzle. This way your searching eyes will move around the screen.

@{" Installation " link "installation"}
@{" Parameters   " link "parameters"  }
@{" Author       " link "author"      }
@{" Copyright    " link "copyright"   }
@{" Disclaimer   " link "disclaimer"  }
@{" Future       " link "future"      }
@{" History      " link "history"     }

WARNING:
This module needs constant access to the screen it cloned.
Therefore it _can_ happen that the module crashes the system.
This occurs, if the program using the cloned screen closes
it again while the module is blanking.
Currently I know of only one way to circumvent this:
Opening a little window on that screen. But that would block
that screen and in the above rare case you'd get a dead
screen lying around.
In fact, I don't think that there are much programs that close
their screen without asking the user. I use it myself and up
to now I've never had any problems.
If you encounter real problems with this behaviour, email me
and I'll implement the little blocking window.
(In fact, you are able to switch the updating off, if you want.
If you do so, this module should never cause any problems ;-)
See the @{"parameters" link "parameters"} section for details.)
@endnode

@node "installation" "LivingShuffle.guide/installation"
First unpack the archive with:
    lha -xa x Living.lha ram:
(Probably you've done that already.)

Then double-click on the "install" icon and follow the instructions.


If you really want to do it all manually, read on:
Just copy the files:
    LivingShuffle.ifc
    LivingShuffle.prefs
    LivingShuffle.txt
to the directory containing your Garshneblanker modules.
Additionally you should copy one of the three files
    LivingShuffle
    LivingShuffle020
    LivingShuffle030
to the same directory as 'LivingShuffle' depending on which cpu you
have. So for a plain 68000 cpu you just copy 'LivingShuffle' to the
module directory. If you have an 68030 you copy 'LivingShuffle030'
to that directory and rename it to 'LivingShuffle'.
The file
    LivingShuffle.guide
contains this documentation. Copy it where you want
(if you want :)
If you are interested in the source code then create a subdirectory
    LivingShuffle
in your development directory dev/garshneblanker/blankers/
Copy the contents of the
    dev
directory of this archive there.


That's all.
To see it working just use exchange to open Garshneblanker's
front-end, click on "settings" then on "save" and finally select
"LivingShuffle" from the menu via a left button double click.
I think the gadgets are quite self-explanatory.
If not, see the @{"parameters" link parameters} section of this guide.
@endnode

@node "parameters" "LivingShuffle.guide/Parameters"
À Cycle gadget <no name>
        Update pieces continuously
            -> During each shuffle step each of the pieces gets
               actualized graphics directly from the cloned source
               screen below. So you keep in touch with your latest
               front screen even while blanking and shuffling!
               (Can cause system crash, if the source screen closes
               while this module is blanking.)
               This results in slower movement and some flickering,
               especially on high colour screens
        Do only a simple shuffle
            -> After the screen is cloned, the usual simple shuffle
               starts, like you know it from other blankers
               Faster and causes never any crashes :)
        default: Update pieces continuously

À Slider "Columns"
        2..50 -> Number of columns of the puzzle
                 (If the screen is too small, this value is adjusted
                 automatically. All pieces are at least 8 pixels
                 wide.)
        default: 10

À Slider "Rows"
        2..50 -> Number of rows of the puzzle
                 (If the screen is too small, this value is adjusted
                 automatically. All pieces are at least 8 pixels
                 tall.)
        default: 8

À Slider "Divisions"
        1..50 -> Number of steps for one shuffle move
                 The more divisions you select, the slower the piece
                 will move but the smoother the movement will seem.
                 (Too high division values will be decreased
                 automatically, to prevent the pieces from making
                 pauses in their movement.)
        default: 10

À Cycle gadget "Hole filling"
        Always background colour
            -> The hole is always filled with background colour
        Randomly select a colour once
            -> On module startup one colour of the cloned screen is
               selected and used for the holes, so each hole will
               look the same.
        Randomly select for each hole a new colour
            -> For each hole that occurrs, a colour of the screen
               is randomly selected. Now each hole looks different.
        default: Always background colour

À Cycle gadget "Draw piece borders"
        Yes -> Around each piece a border is drawn, looking as if
               light shines from the topleft on it
        No  -> No borders are drawn around pieces
               In this way every pixel of the precious shuffle screen
               is visible :)
        default: Yes

À Slider "Delay"
        1..100 -> Number of TICKS to wait between two steps of
                  movement. (50 means approx. one second)
                  (If you would like to select more than 100 email me,
                  I will change this value - but tell me what for an
                  Amiga you've got!!! :-)
                  (In fact a delay by 1 is no delay, a delay by 50
                  means 49 ticks, etc.)
        default: 1

À Cycle gadget "Screen"
        Top Screen
            -> The frontmost screen is cloned and used for
               shuffling.
        Default Public
            -> The default public screen is cloned and used for
               shuffling. (usually this is the workbench.)
               starts, like you know it from other blankers
               Faster and causes never any crashes :)
        default: Top Screen

À Slider "Fade %"
        0..99 -> Percent of colour fading
                 The higher the value the darker the screen.
                 (This is implemented to have the right to call
                 this module a "screen blanking/saving module" ;-)
        default: 25
@endnode


